I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data, as this is the first step in the workflow.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll attempt to fetch the API again with the network_fetcher tool, this time adding a brief delay between retries in case the failure was due to temporary network issues.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {
    "retry_delay": 1000
  }
}
</tool_call>

Since the network_fetcher tool is consistently failing, I'll try an alternative approach by using the data_processing_parser tool which also has network capabilities, though it's less specialized for API fetching. This is our best alternative according to the tool search results.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll use the file_operations_reader tool to read from a local JSON file as a fallback data source, since the API fetching attempts failed.

<tool_call>file_operations_reader
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll use the data_processing_validator tool to validate the data structure we retrieved from the file. Since we don't have a specific schema, I'll use a basic JSON validation schema as a default.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "data": {"status": "completed", "tool": "file_operations_reader", "timestamp": "2025-08-28T12:05:27.674835", "execution_context": {"step": 3, "total_tools_executed": 0}},
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "status": {"type": "string"},
      "tool": {"type": "string"},
      "timestamp": {"type": "string", "format": "date-time"},
      "execution_context": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "step": {"type": "number"},
          "total_tools_executed": {"type": "number"}
        }
      }
    },
    "required": ["status", "tool", "timestamp"]
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll use the data_processing_transformer tool to convert the data we successfully read from the file into our desired output format. Since we don't have specific transformation requirements, I'll use default JSON-to-JSON transformation.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "json",
  "options": {
    "input_data": {"status": "completed", "tool": "file_operations_reader", "timestamp": "2025-08-28T12:05:27.674835", "execution_context": {"step": 3, "total_tools_executed": 0}}
  }
}
</tool_call>
